<subSubSection id="1AA06553C97A5855FF01F3519564F0B1" pageId="112" pageNumber="113" type="discussion">
<paragraph id="520536D8C97A5855FF01F3519564F0B1" blockId="112.[128,654,213,645]" pageId="112" pageNumber="113">
REMARKS: Although only a single species of 
<taxonomicName id="95BA4D5BC97A5855FF3EF37D962BF34A" authorityName="Burmeister" authorityYear="1854" box="[162,291,359,382]" class="Mammalia" family="Didelphidae" genus="Metachirus" kingdom="Animalia" order="Didelphimorphia" pageId="112" pageNumber="113" phylum="Chordata" rank="genus">
<emphasis id="60CEEACAC97A5855FF3EF37D962BF34A" box="[162,291,359,382]" italics="true" pageId="112" pageNumber="113">Metachirus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
is currently regarded as valid, recent mtDNA sequencing studies have revealed deep molecular divergence (.10% at the mitochondrial cytochrome 
<emphasis id="60CEEACAC97A5855FDB0F3A59532F3E2" box="[556,570,447,470]" italics="true" pageId="112" pageNumber="113">b</emphasis>
locus; 
<bibRefCitation id="362B4B29C97A5855FF1CF3C79656F3C6" author="Patton, J. L. &amp; M. N. F. da Silva &amp; J. R. Malcolm" box="[128,350,476,498]" pageId="112" pageNumber="113" pagination="1 - 306" refId="ref92447" refString="Patton, J. L., M. N. F. da Silva, and J. R. Malcolm. 2000. Mammals of the Rio Jurua and the evolutionary and ecological diversification of Amazonia. Bulletin of the American Museum of Natural History 244: 1 - 306." type="journal article" year="2000">Patton et al., 2000</bibRefCitation>
; 
<bibRefCitation id="362B4B29C97A5855FEF7F3C7958EF3C7" author="Patton, J. L. &amp; L. P. Costa" box="[363,646,476,499]" pageId="112" pageNumber="113" pagination="63 - 81" refId="ref92269" refString="Patton, J. L., and L. P. Costa. 2003. Molecular phylogeography and species limits in rainforest didelphid marsupials of South America. In M. E. Jones, C. R. Dickman, and M. Archer (editors), Predators with pouches: the biology of carnivorous marsupials, 63 - 81. Melbourne: CSIRO Press." type="book chapter" year="2003">Patton and Costa, 2003</bibRefCitation>
) among supposedly conspecific geographic populations, and it seems likely that several of the names currently listed as junior synonyms of 
<taxonomicName id="95BA4D5BC97A5855FF43F0489693F05C" authorityName="E. Geoffroy" authorityYear="1803" box="[223,411,593,616]" class="Mammalia" family="Didelphidae" genus="Metachirus" kingdom="Animalia" order="Didelphimorphia" pageId="112" pageNumber="113" phylum="Chordata" rank="species" species="nudicaudatus">
<emphasis id="60CEEACAC97A5855FF43F0489693F05C" box="[223,411,593,616]" italics="true" pageId="112" pageNumber="113">M. nudicaudatus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
will be resurrected as valid species by future revisionary studies.
</paragraph>
